# @text, @text, @text, @text, @question, @text, @true_false, @reflect, @text
# Variant E (3 steps), default intro, teaching: system 1 and system 2

@text
Somewhere in every head, a quiet negotiation runs all day long.
Two minds share the same room, and one of them is always in the driver's seat.
The fast mind answers in a heartbeat.
The slow mind only shows up when forced.
Most of any day is decided by the faster one, and nobody ever notices.

@text
A small test, first.
A baseball bat and a ball cost $1.10 together.
The bat costs $1 more than the ball.
The question arrives, and an answer arrives with it.
Most people say 10 cents, instantly, without pausing.
The answer is wrong. The correct answer is 5 cents.
Nobody was asked to check it, and nobody did.

@text
Now a different kind of task.
A friend in a red coat is somewhere inside a busy train station.
The eyes scan crowd after crowd.
Strangers fade, the noise fades, and only red keeps making it through.
After a few minutes, the red coat appears.
That kind of looking takes effort, and every second of it can be felt.

@text
Two minds, two speeds, two futures in every moment.
The fast mind returned the 10-cent answer without being asked to do anything.
The slow mind did the work of pulling the red coat out of the crowd.
The faster the fast mind feels, the less the slow mind ever gets called.
The less the slow mind gets called, the more the fast one answers alone.
The more it answers alone, the more small errors quietly pile up.

@question
Why does the answer "10 cents" arrive so quickly for most people?

answer: The question is too simple to think about carefully.
consequence: The fast answer feels simple, but the correct answer is 5 cents. The question was a trap.

answer: The fast intuitive mind answered before the slow careful mind was called.
consequence: The fast mind returned the first plausible number, and the slow mind was never invited in.

answer: Most adults have forgotten basic subtraction.
consequence: The math itself is easy. The problem is that nobody reached for the math.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The fast mind hands in an answer that feels right. The slow mind would have checked it, and the fast one got there first.
hint: Consider which of the two kinds of thinking answered before any subtraction happened.

@text
The fast and the slow minds are the two characters the course keeps circling back to.
<c:g>System 1</c:g> is the fast one, answering the bat-and-ball question before any math begins.
System 2 is the slow one, doing the work of finding the red coat in a crowd.
System 1 is awake every waking moment.
System 2 is expensive to run, and the brain spares it whenever it can.
Every quiet trouble in this course starts when System 1 answers a question that needed System 2.

@true_false
Most everyday decisions are handled by the slow, deliberate side of thinking.

true: True
consequence: Running the slow mind all day would be exhausting. The fast mind handles most of it without help.

false: False
consequence: The slow mind is expensive, and the brain leaves the driving to the fast one whenever it can.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The fast mind is the default driver. The slow mind is called in only when the situation demands careful work.
hint: Think about how tired anyone would feel after running the slow mind for a whole day.

@reflect
A moment when the fast answer arrived before real thought: a first impression at a party.
A task that really needed the slow mind: filling in a tax form at night.
A small decision the fast mind made alone: picking the same lunch three days in a row.

@text
Two minds, one head, one driver most of the time.
The slow mind could step in at any moment, and it almost never does.
What happens when the fast one runs the show unchecked is the rest of this story.

@package
Why the Bat Felt So Simple
# @text, @text, @text, @question, @pause, @text, @true_false, @text
# Variant G (thought experiment), misconception intro, teaching: the law of least effort

@text
Most people who read the bat-and-ball question answer <c:r>10 cents</c:r> and move on.
The number feels right.
The sum looks clean.
The slow mind is right there in the head, and still nothing in it ever switches on.

@text
Imagine the same question put to a room full of trained mathematicians.
About half of them also answer 10 cents on a first reading.
The math is easy.
The trap is that 10 cents looks so obvious that nobody bothers to test it.
If the ball were 10 cents, the bat would be $1.10, totalling $1.20.
The correct answer is 5 cents, and checking it takes real effort.

@text
Now imagine the same room solving the question while walking on a treadmill.
The wrong-answer rate goes up.
The slow mind pulls energy from the same pool as the walking legs.
When the body is busy, the slow mind is slower to show up.
Tired people make more thinking mistakes than rested ones.
A small law runs in the background of every moment of the day.

@question
How does the bat-and-ball question fool so many thoughtful adults?

answer: The wording of the question is misleading and unfair.
consequence: The wording is plain English. The trap is in how cheaply the fast mind hands over an answer.

answer: The fast mind supplies a clean-looking answer and the slow mind does not bother to check.
consequence: The fast mind signs off early. The slow mind would catch the error, if it were ever asked.

answer: Most people do not know how to subtract cents from dollars.
consequence: The subtraction is easy for any adult. The missing step is deciding to subtract at all.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The fast mind hands in a plausible answer. The slow mind would catch it, and costs effort, so it stays off.
hint: Consider what the slow mind would have to do, and why it might decide not to.

@pause
A long walk or a hungry afternoon quietly drains the same fuel careful thinking is supposed to run on.

@text
<c:g>The law of least effort</c:g> is the quiet rule the two minds obey.
The fast mind handles what it can for almost no cost.
The slow mind handles the rest, and only when the fast one cannot fake it.
Running the slow mind is tiring, and the brain lets the fast one sign off whenever the answer looks clean.
That is how a $1.10 question catches a mathematician on a tired Friday afternoon.

@true_false
People who are tired or distracted tend to make more thinking errors on simple logic tests.

true: True
consequence: When the slow mind has no budget left, the fast mind answers alone, and its errors show.

false: False
consequence: Tiredness drains the slow mind first, and the fast one is the one left answering.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: The slow mind shares energy with the rest of the body. A tired head lets the fast mind answer unchecked.
hint: Think about what a long walk or a hungry afternoon does to careful thinking.

@text
The fast mind is cheap, and that is why it runs the show.
The slow mind is where most good thinking lives, and it shows up late and leaves early.
A quieter question follows: what happens when the head is not tired, and still feels at ease?

@package
Between Easy and Awake
# @text, @text, @text, @question, @text, @true_false, @reflect, @text
# Variant C (2 stories), default intro, teaching: cognitive ease

@text
Two menus sit on the same table.
One is printed in a clean, sharp font.
The other is printed on dark paper in a tight grey font.
The food on both is identical.
The reader is already thinking differently about each one.

@text
A group of students sits down for a short logic test.
Half of them get the test in a clean, sharp font.
The other half get the same questions in a faded, hard-to-read font.
The second group makes fewer careless mistakes.
The eye strains.
The slow mind wakes up on its own and catches what the fast one missed.

@text
Now the same effect runs the other way.
A claim printed in a clear font feels more believable than the same claim printed awkwardly.
A rhyme feels truer than a plain sentence saying the same thing.
A second reading feels more true than the first.
The head mistakes smoothness for truth.
Ease and confidence are easy to confuse from the inside.

@question
Why does a hard-to-read font help a reader catch careless errors?

answer: The reader slows down and the slow mind steps in on its own.
consequence: Strain is a small alarm. The slow mind wakes up to handle what the fast mind cannot read cleanly.

answer: The reader gives up and guesses, which happens to be more accurate.
consequence: Readers with the hard font catch more errors, because the strain wakes the slow mind up.

answer: The harder font contains different information than the easy one.
consequence: Both fonts contain the same words. Only the feeling of effort changes.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: When reading feels smooth, the fast mind signs off early. A bit of strain invites the slow mind to check the work.
hint: Think about what the head does when a sentence suddenly becomes hard to parse.

@text
When the menu reads cleanly, the head is inside <c:g>cognitive ease</c:g>, the fast mind's favourite setting.
It is the feeling that the menu is clear, the story makes sense, and there is nothing to check.
The tight grey font is the opposite setting, cognitive strain, and it invites the slow mind in.
The easier it feels, the less the slow mind steps in.
The harder it feels, the faster the slow mind walks through the door.
A smoothly-written lie can feel truer than an awkward truth, purely because it reads easier.

@true_false
Statements printed in clear, familiar fonts are more often rated as true than the same statements printed awkwardly.

true: True
consequence: The head mistakes the ease of reading for the truth of the claim. The slow mind rarely catches this.

false: False
consequence: The feeling of easy reading quietly lifts the believability of the claim underneath it.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: A sentence that reads smoothly feels truer than the same sentence printed awkwardly. The head reads ease as trust.
hint: Think about how a rhyme or a clean font changes how a claim feels.

@reflect
A claim believed without checking because it sounded clean: a slogan heard twice in one week.
A time when strain forced real thinking: a confusing foreign street sign demanding full attention.
A message that feels truer each time: an advert played between every song on the radio.

@text
Ease is the fast mind's home setting.
Thinking runs cheaper there, and the door is wide open for anything that slips in.
A single word on a page, read in passing, can change the next word that comes to mind.

@package
What One Word Can Do...
# @true_false, @text, @text, @text, @question, @pause, @text, @text
# Variant D (3 stories), true/false intro, teaching: priming

@true_false
Reading a single unrelated word can change which word a person thinks of next.

true: True
consequence: The head keeps a quiet trail of recent words ready, and the next guess is pulled from it.

false: False
consequence: Recent words leave a soft trail that the next guess follows, even when the person never notices.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: One recent word can bias the next one that comes to mind. The fast mind fills blanks from what is near at hand.
hint: Consider what the head does with a word just read, without being asked to remember it.

@text
Someone is shown the letters SO_P and asked to fill in the blank.
A moment earlier they read the word EAT, and they write SOUP.
A different person, a moment earlier, read the word SHOWER, and they write SOAP.
The letters have not changed.
The recent word has quietly reached into the head and pulled the next one out.

@text
A second experiment raises the stakes.
A group of adults walks into a room to solve a short puzzle.
The puzzle is sprinkled with the words old, Florida, wrinkle, and grey.
After finishing, each person walks back down the hallway to leave.
Those who read the old-words puzzle walk noticeably slower than those who did not.
Nobody was told to slow down. The words did the pushing on their own.

@text
A third experiment moves the trick into mood.
A small picture of money sits on the desk in a plain research room.
People working under that picture ask less often for help on a hard task.
They also help less when a stranger drops a pencil nearby.
Nobody mentions money, and nobody notices the picture after a minute.
The image alone nudges the head into an independent mood, and every decision rides on that mood.

@question
Where does the pull toward writing SOUP or SOAP actually come from?

answer: From a conscious decision the person made but quickly forgot.
consequence: The person had no sense of deciding anything. The pull came from the recent word left in the head.

answer: From a quiet trail the recent word left behind, which the fast mind follows automatically.
consequence: The last word read leaves the head slightly readier for nearby ideas, and the next guess is pulled from them.

answer: From the shape of the letters on the page, not from the earlier word.
consequence: The letters are the same for everyone. Only the earlier word changed between the two groups.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: A recent word leaves a soft trail, and the fast mind fills the next blank from what is readiest. No choice happens.
hint: Ask where the difference between SOAP and SOUP could have come from, given identical letters.

@pause
A picture on a desk can colour a whole afternoon of small decisions without anyone looking at it twice.

@text
A single word left a trail strong enough to steer the next one, and that trail is called <c:g>priming</c:g>.
EAT walks a reader into writing SOUP a moment later.
Old-words puzzles slow a young person's walk down a hallway.
A picture of money nudges a whole room into a more independent mood.
The trail runs under the slow mind, never crossing its path.
Most of daily life is steered by these quiet nudges, from posters to the people in the room.

@text
The fast mind is a surface.
Whatever lands on it leaves a mark, and the next thought rides over that mark.
What happens when the fast mind only has a single first impression of a stranger is the next question.

@package
More Than the Answer Deserved
# @text, @text, @question, @text, @true_false, @reflect, @text
# Variant B (2 beats), skip intro, teaching: the halo effect

@text
Ben was introduced at a friend's dinner on a quiet Thursday evening.
He laughed easily, asked good questions, and remembered the name of every person at the table.
By the end of the night, three other guests would have said Ben was clearly intelligent.
None of them had seen Ben solve a single problem or make a single decision.
What they had seen was a warm voice, kind eyes, and a good memory for names.

@text
A week later, one of the guests is asked if Ben would be good for a small charity board.
The answer comes back quickly, a confident yes.
Another is asked if Ben would be trustworthy with money, and the answer is again a quick yes.
A third is asked if Ben would make a steady business partner, and again the answer is yes.
Nobody at the dinner had any evidence about boards, money, or business.

@question
What are the guests really answering when they say Ben would be good for the charity board?

answer: A careful judgment, built from the small amount they know about Ben.
consequence: The dinner showed nothing about charity work or budgets. The careful judgment was never really made.

answer: A broad good feeling about Ben, stretched over every new question about him.
consequence: One warm impression spreads over every new question, even when the question is about something unseen.

answer: A guess based on the kind of person who usually sits on charity boards.
consequence: The guests were asked about Ben, not about the average board member. Their warm feeling answered for him.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: A single warm impression can cover every later question about the person. The fast mind fills each answer from the same feeling.
hint: Think about how little Ben was actually seen doing, and how broad the guests' answers still were.

@text
What Ben collected at the dinner has a name, <c:g>the halo effect</c:g>, the fast mind's favourite shortcut with strangers.
One warm half-hour becomes the answer to questions about charity boards a week later.
The same half-hour becomes the answer to questions about money.
The same half-hour becomes the answer to questions about business.
The fast mind prefers one clear feeling to a messy mix of evidence.
Once the feeling is set, every new question meets it first and comes out coloured by it.

@true_false
A single good first impression tends to colour later judgments about the same person, even in unrelated areas.

true: True
consequence: The fast mind likes one neat feeling per person. Once set, every new question meets it first.

false: False
consequence: Clean separate judgments would cost effort. The fast mind smooths them into one warm or cool impression.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: A first impression is hard to spend only once. The fast mind carries it into judgments it never earned.
hint: Think about how a warm rating on one topic tends to spread to unrelated topics too.

@reflect
A new colleague trusted on thin evidence because the first week felt friendly: a coffee chat.
A stranger judged on one awkward moment for a likely dull reason: a rushed crosswalk wave.
A small warm detail that quietly bought someone a lot of trust: a handwritten thank-you note.

@text
The two minds have been sketched, and their favourite shortcut has been named.
The same shortcut shows up again where no stranger is in the room at all.
It is there whenever a number quietly walks into a question, and that is where the next chapter starts.

@segment
The Quiet Distortions
QD

@package
When the Easier Question Wins
# @text, @text, @text, @question, @text, @true_false, @reflect, @text
# Variant A (2 scenes), default intro, teaching: the substitution heuristic

@text
A hard question and an easy question often look almost identical from the outside.
The head cannot always tell which one it is really answering.
A lot of confident opinions come out of that small confusion.

@text
Imagine standing in a voting booth with a name on the ballot that nobody knows well.
"Will this candidate make a good sheriff for the next four years?"
Picture the face, the haircut, the tone of voice in the campaign video.
Notice how quickly a yes or no starts to form.
Almost nobody in that booth is answering the real question.
They are answering a much easier one, "Does this person look like a sheriff?"

@text
Now picture someone looking at a new job offer at their kitchen table.
The real question is, "Will I still feel good about this job in two years?"
That question is heavy, uncertain, and costs real thinking.
The head quietly swaps it for a lighter one, "Do I feel good about this job right now?"
The easy one gets an answer in seconds.
The answer is then served as if it had addressed the harder question all along.

@question
Why does the sheriff question end up being answered so quickly?

answer: Because the voter is an expert on sheriffs and recognises a good one.
consequence: Most voters have no expertise in sheriffs. Something else is doing the answering.

answer: Because the head quietly swaps the hard question for an easy one about appearance.
consequence: A hard question about four years of work is replaced by an easy one about a face.

answer: Because sheriffs all look roughly the same and the choice does not matter.
consequence: Sheriffs vary widely. The shortcut has nothing to do with real similarity between candidates.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The head replaces a hard question with an easier one it can answer fast. The answer from the easy one then stands in for the harder one.
hint: Ask what question the voter could actually answer in one glance at a campaign photo.

@text
<c:g>The substitution heuristic</c:g> is the quiet swap in the voting booth when "good sheriff" becomes "sheriff-looking face."
It is the kitchen-table swap when "good in two years" becomes "good right now."
The head answers the lighter question and hands the answer to the heavier one.
Nobody notices the trade, and the confident answer still feels like real thinking.
The fast mind's fastest trick leaves no trace, and the slow mind almost never looks for one.

@true_false
When people answer a hard question quickly, they usually answered a related, easier question without realising it.

true: True
consequence: The fast mind finds the closest question it can handle and substitutes it in without asking.

false: False
consequence: Real thought takes more time than a one-second opinion. The quick answer came from a lighter question.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: A hard question gets quietly swapped for a near one that the fast mind can answer. The answer feels like real judgment.
hint: Think about how long the hard question would really take, and how short the quick answer was.

@reflect
A strong opinion about a stranger formed in a minute: a driver from a brief ride home.
A career choice steered by how one office day felt: a Friday afternoon with cheerful colleagues.
A house bought for how the kitchen smelled at the viewing: fresh bread during the visit.

@text
The easy-question swap is one doorway into confident answers built on almost nothing.
Another doorway swings open whenever the head has to guess how often something happens in the world.
The answer, most of the time, is whatever comes to mind first.

@package
Picking the Vivid Over the True
# @text, @text, @text, @text, @pause, @text, @true_false, @text
# Variant D (3 stories), default intro, teaching: the availability heuristic

@text
An old news report plays in the background during breakfast.
A small plane has crashed overnight, and the footage shows the broken fuselage in a field.
For three days, the same footage loops on every channel at the top of every hour.
That week, something quietly shifts in how many people book flights.

@text
A man is asked, "What is more likely to kill someone, a stroke or an accident?"
He thinks for a moment.
"An accident, probably," he says.
Accidents are everywhere on film, in the news, and on the evening bulletin.
Strokes happen far more often, and always quietly, in hospitals and in homes.
The head counts the dramatic pictures and forgets the quiet ones.

@text
A shark is spotted off a quiet beach.
The sighting makes the local news for a day.
That summer, fewer swimmers go in the water.
The actual shark count has not changed.
The picture of a fin above the water is now easy to call to mind.
The head treats that ease as a measure of how real the danger is.

@text
A homeowner is asked how likely it is that their roof will leak this year.
If the neighbour's roof leaked two months ago, the answer comes back high.
If nobody nearby has had a leak, the same homeowner quietly rates the chance as low.
The actual roof, the weather, and the tiles have not changed.
Only the picture in the head has, and the picture is doing the math.

@pause
The evening news is a slow tide that reshapes the ordinary over months without anyone noticing.

@text
The flight bookings, the shark-free summer, and the worried homeowner all bent to <c:g>the availability heuristic</c:g>.
It is the oldest shortcut the fast mind uses, older than any news cycle.
The head treats how easily a picture comes up as a rough measure of how often it happens.
The more vivid the picture, the higher the rating, even when the picture is rare.
The dull common thing loses every time to the sharp rare thing.

@true_false
People tend to rate deaths from dramatic causes such as plane crashes as more likely than deaths from quiet causes such as strokes.

true: True
consequence: The head uses ease of recall as the measure. Dramatic causes come to mind faster, so they look common.

false: False
consequence: Statistics are hard to recall. Pictures come back easily, and the fast mind uses them instead.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: The fast mind counts by pictures, and not by numbers. Dramatic pictures are always near at hand, so their causes seem more common.
hint: Think about which causes of death appear most often in films, and which almost never do.

@text
Easy-to-picture dangers quietly inflate, and dull-to-picture ones quietly shrink.
The same trick is waiting behind the next story, this time about numbers hiding in plain sight.
The fast mind is about to meet a rare colour of taxi.

@package
Behind the Headline Number
# @text, @text, @text, @question, @text, @true_false, @text
# Variant G (thought experiment), skip intro, teaching: base-rate neglect

@text
Suppose a small city runs 100 taxis, all the same model.
80 of the taxis are red, and 20 are yellow.
The taxis are dispatched at random, and none of the drivers prefer one colour.
A taxi is called to a house, and the caller is told the next one will arrive in 10 minutes.

@text
Suppose the caller has just watched 5 red taxis pass down the street in a row.
The caller thinks, "Surely the next one must be yellow, for a change."
That feeling is strong, and many people in that spot would share it.
The company has not changed the 80-to-20 split.
The next taxi has roughly an 80% chance of being red, like every taxi before it.
The string of red taxis changes nothing about the pool they come from.

@text
Now suppose a taxi is reported in a small accident at night.
A witness says the taxi was yellow.
Under poor lighting, witnesses get taxi colour right about 80% of the time.
Most listeners conclude the taxi was probably yellow.
They skip a quiet question, "What fraction of the taxis in the fleet are yellow?"
Because yellow is only 20% of the fleet, the odds are actually against the witness.

@question
What are most listeners ignoring when they trust the witness and conclude the taxi was yellow?

answer: The witness has a personal reason to lie about the colour.
consequence: The witness may be honest. The problem is a number missing from the story, the share of yellow cabs.

answer: The background share of yellow and red taxis in the city.
consequence: Yellow taxis are rare across the fleet. The witness's accuracy has to be weighed against how unlikely yellow already is.

answer: The lighting conditions on the night of the accident.
consequence: The lighting is already built into the 80% accuracy figure. The missing number is something else entirely.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The base rate, 20% yellow, is the quiet number doing most of the work. Without it, the witness's claim seems stronger than it is.
hint: Ask which number the story is quietly leaving out, the one about the whole fleet.

@text
The trap the taxis set has a name, <c:g>base-rate neglect</c:g>, one of the fast mind's loudest blind spots.
It is the move that drops the 80 red and 20 yellow out of the picture.
The head latches onto the vivid detail in front of it, and forgets the field of numbers behind.
Every story is being told against a background of base rates, and the fast mind almost never looks at it.
The last red taxi wins the thinking, and the 80-to-20 fleet is left out.

@true_false
After seeing five red taxis in a row, the next taxi is more likely to be yellow than it was before.

true: True
consequence: The fleet has not changed. Each taxi is pulled from the same 80-to-20 split as every taxi before.

false: False
consequence: Each taxi is drawn from the same pool. The run of red changes nothing about the pool.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The pool stays the same no matter what has passed. The feeling of "due a yellow" is the fast mind ignoring the base rate.
hint: Ask whether anything has actually changed in the company's fleet between the first taxi and the sixth.

@text
Ignoring the background numbers is only one way the fast mind handles probabilities.
Another is treating a lucky run as if it meant something, and expecting it to keep going.
A hot streak of goals on a football pitch is where that one shows up next.

@package
After the Hot Streak...
# @true_false, @text, @text, @text, @question, @text, @text
# Variant F (historical arc), true/false intro, teaching: regression to the mean

@true_false
A striker who scores far above her usual average in September will almost always keep that form for the rest of the season.

true: True
consequence: A spike is almost always followed by a return to the usual average, not by more spikes.

false: False
consequence: A spike well above average tends to be followed by a drop back toward the usual number.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Any extreme score carries a large share of luck. The next month tends to land closer to the usual rate.
hint: Think about what "average" means for any player, and where a record month sits above it.

@text
A football striker averages 5 goals a month over the last two seasons.
In September of the new season she scores 10, more than any month before.
Teammates celebrate, the local press calls it a breakout, and fans start raising their expectations.
The coach watches quietly, already half-expecting what is coming.

@text
October arrives, and the striker scores 6 goals.
November brings 4, December brings 5.
By Christmas, the season average has quietly settled back around her usual 5.
The local press now talks about a slump, and fans wonder what happened to the hot streak.
The striker has done nothing wrong.
A month of 10 was always going to be followed, most of the time, by something closer to her real rate.

@text
The same quiet pattern runs through classrooms and companies.
A student who does unusually well on one quiz often does less well on the next.
A company that posts its best quarter ever tends to follow it with an ordinary one.
A pilot who lands one flight especially smoothly often lands the next one only averagely well.
None of those people got worse.
The first number was simply further from the truth than the second.

@question
Why does the striker's average month follow her exceptional one?

answer: Teammates stop passing to her because they feel jealous.
consequence: There is no evidence teammates change behaviour. The pattern appears even for players without a team.

answer: The exceptional month carried a lot of luck, and the next month tends to land closer to her real rate.
consequence: A spike is mostly the usual rate plus good luck. The next month keeps the rate and loses the luck.

answer: The striker becomes overconfident after scoring so many goals.
consequence: Overconfidence may happen, and the same pattern appears in players who never knew their own numbers.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Any record-breaking month is partly skill and partly luck. Luck rarely repeats, so the next month drifts back toward the real skill.
hint: Ask how much of an exceptional month is real skill, and how much is weather and luck.

@text
The quiet October after the record September has a name, <c:g>regression to the mean</c:g>.
It is the correction the fast mind keeps forgetting to expect.
It turns the striker's record month into an ordinary one without anyone changing.
It turns the top quiz score of the month into an ordinary one the next week.
The fast mind hates endings without stories, and wants a reason for every drop.
Most of the time there is no reason, only a hot month returning to where it always was.

@text
Regression is hard to hold in the head because it has no story attached.
The fast mind wants a character or a cause, and will invent one if none is there.
The same hunger for stories meets the next trap, where the same fact is dressed in two different sets of words.

@package
Same Fact, Different Frame
# @text, @text, @text, @question, @pause, @text, @true_false, @reflect, @text
# Variant E (mechanism walkthrough), default intro, teaching: framing effects

@text
A doctor can describe a treatment in two equally accurate ways.
The first, "90% of patients survive the first year."
The second, "10% of patients die within the first year."
The numbers are identical.
The choice that follows usually differs.

@text
A group of psychiatric professionals is asked about releasing a patient named Mr. Jones.
Half are told, "Patients like Mr. Jones have a 10% probability of committing an act of violence."
The other half are told, "Of every 100 patients like Mr. Jones, 10 will commit an act of violence."
The two sentences describe the same risk.
Yet the group hearing about "10 out of every 100" is almost twice as likely to block the release.
The second wording forces the head to picture 10 real people, and 10 real people feel heavier than a 10% probability.

@text
The same shift runs through everyday choices.
A shop selling "ground beef, 85% lean" sells better than the same beef labelled "15% fat."
A surgeon with a 90% survival rate is chosen over one with a 10% death rate.
A warning of "1 in 10,000 children will be permanently disfigured" worries parents more than a 0.01% chance of disfigurement.
The information is identical.
The picture the sentence forms in the head is what decides.

@question
How can two sentences with the same numbers lead to different decisions?

answer: One sentence must contain a subtle extra piece of information.
consequence: Both sentences contain the same numbers. The difference lives in the picture, and the picture decides.

answer: The wording shapes the picture in the head, and the picture, not the numbers, does the deciding.
consequence: The fast mind works from pictures. Two different pictures from the same numbers lead to two different decisions.

answer: The listener does not understand percentages properly.
consequence: The listeners in these studies understood the percentages. The wording still changed their decisions.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Two sentences can share their numbers and still build very different pictures. The picture is what the fast mind reaches for.
hint: Think about which of the two sentences makes a specific person easier to picture.

@pause
A number by itself is a short sentence the head has to finish before it can be judged.

@text
The doctor's two sentences and the Mr. Jones study both ran on <c:g>framing</c:g>, a shortcut the fast mind cannot avoid.
It is the shift that turns "90% survive" into a safer option than "10% die," even when the outcomes match.
It is also the shift that turns "10 in 100" into more real people than "10%."
The fast mind cannot see a number without picturing something, and the picture is already deciding.
The slow mind could check the numbers, and often does not, because the picture already feels like enough.

@true_false
A treatment described as "90% survival" and one described as "10% death rate" lead most people to make the same choice.

true: True
consequence: The outcomes match. The pictures they build differ, and the death-rate version is chosen less often.

false: False
consequence: Wording shapes the picture, and the picture shapes the choice. The numbers rarely get the last word.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: People, including doctors, choose less often when risk is framed as death than when the same risk is framed as survival.
hint: Think about which of the two sentences places a living patient at the centre of the picture.

@reflect
A meal seen differently after someone read its label aloud: "85% lean" versus "15% fat."
A policy that sounded sharper after a number was restated: "10 out of 100 families."
A risk that felt smaller as a percentage than as a count: "0.01%" versus "1 in 10,000."

@text
The same picture-first habit runs through every place where money, risk, or loss is at stake.
A loss sketched clearly in the mind weighs more than a gain of equal size.
Even on paper the two rarely feel equal, and that small asymmetry shapes most of the big decisions a person ever makes.

@package
Why Losing Hurts Louder
# @text, @text, @text, @question, @text, @true_false, @reflect, @text
# Variant B (2 beats), misconception intro, teaching: loss aversion

@text
Most people assume a $100 win and a $100 loss <c:r>cancel out evenly inside the head</c:r>.
The math says they should.
Anyone who has lost $100 on the bus home already knows the head does not run on math.

@text
A small test is offered at a cafe.
The deal is a coin flip, heads wins $150, tails loses $100.
On pure math, the flip is clearly good, the expected value is positive.
Very few people take it.
The idea of losing $100 weighs more, inside the head, than the idea of winning $150.
The imagined pain of the loss is louder than the imagined pleasure of the win.

@text
Now picture the same person handed $1,000 up front.
The choice is to walk away with $500, or flip a coin for $1,000 or nothing.
Most people take the sure $500.
Now picture the same person handed $2,000, with two new options.
The choice is to lose $500, or flip to lose $1,000 or nothing.
Most people flip the coin.
Both outcomes are identical on paper.

@question
Where is the real difference between the two $1,000 choices coming from?

answer: The two offers lead to different amounts of money at the end.
consequence: The ending positions are identical in both cases. Only the story around them has changed.

answer: The head sees one offer as a gain and the other as a loss, and treats them very differently.
consequence: A gain frame and a loss frame lead to different decisions, even when the money ends up at the same place.

answer: The person suddenly becomes braver in the second scenario for no reason.
consequence: Framing the outcome as a loss, a loss the coin can undo, makes the same risk feel worth taking.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The same final position can be a gain or a loss depending on the starting point. A loss the coin could cancel feels worth risking.
hint: Compare how each scenario feels, beyond the numbers at the end.

@text
What turned the cafe flip into a walk-away deal is <c:g>loss aversion</c:g>, the loudest shortcut the fast mind takes.
The same $500 feels safe in a gain frame and unbearable in a loss frame.
A loss weighs roughly twice as much in the head as a gain of the same size.
The slow mind can run the math, and the fast mind has already decided how the numbers hurt.
By the time the calculator is reached for, the answer is already felt.

@true_false
Most people would happily take a coin flip that wins $150 on heads and loses $100 on tails.

true: True
consequence: The math is positive, and loss aversion makes most people refuse. A possible $100 loss feels heavier than a likely $150 gain.

false: False
consequence: The pain of the possible loss outweighs the pleasure of the larger gain, and most people walk away.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: People refuse flips that are clearly good on math because the imagined loss weighs more than the imagined win.
hint: Think about how long the memory of losing $100 would linger, compared to winning $150.

@reflect
A small cost avoided more than a larger gain was chased: a subscription kept to skip cancelling.
An asset held at a small loss while it kept falling: a gadget kept past its value.
A life change delayed because the loss felt louder than the gain: a job never applied to.

@text
The whole course has been tracking the same two minds, the fast and the slow, and the quiet trades they make.
One trade is left, and it shapes what the head keeps of any experience after it ends.
The story remembered is almost never the story that was actually lived.

@package
The Story We Keep
# @text, @text, @text, @question, @text, @true_false, @text
# Variant C (2 stories), default intro, teaching: the peak-end rule

@text
A good holiday and a painful dentist visit are remembered through the same quiet filter.
Neither is recalled the way it was lived, minute by minute.
The head keeps a compressed story, and the compression always follows a few simple rules.

@text
Two patients go through the same uncomfortable procedure on the same day.
The first has a short version that ends at its most painful moment.
The second has a longer version that starts painful, and eases off at the end.
The second patient spends more total time in pain.
Asked later, the second patient remembers it as noticeably less awful.
The ending, and the single worst moment, do most of the remembering.

@text
Two tourists return from the same 7-day trip to a coastal town.
The first had a good week, with one magical boat ride on day 3 and a quiet flight home on day 7.
The second had a good week, with an ordinary boat ride on day 3 and a missed flight on day 7.
The first remembers the trip as one of the best of her life.
The second remembers the trip as a disaster.
The first 5 days, identical for both, have faded into the background of the story.

@question
What does the head actually use to rate how good or bad an experience was?

answer: A careful average of every minute of the experience.
consequence: The head does not keep minute-by-minute averages. Most of the middle of any experience is lost almost at once.

answer: The peak moment and the ending, which together stand in for the whole experience.
consequence: The sharpest moment and the final moment do most of the remembering. Everything between them fades quickly.

answer: The first moments of the experience, because first impressions are the strongest.
consequence: First impressions matter in meeting a person. For rating an experience, the peak and the ending win.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The memory of any experience collapses into a single peak and a single ending. The middle, and the total length, fade almost entirely.
hint: Compare how much weight the dentist's last minute carries compared to every other minute.

@text
The dentist's patients and the tourists share <c:g>the peak-end rule</c:g>, the quietest shortcut the fast mind leaves behind.
The longer, gentler dentist visit is remembered as kinder than the shorter, sharper one.
The week is rated from a boat ride and a final flight.
The head keeps the sharpest moment and the final one, and quietly throws the rest away.
A very good decade can be remembered badly if its last week goes wrong.
A hard project can be loved in memory if it ends well.

@true_false
A shorter unpleasant experience that ends at its worst moment is usually remembered as worse than a longer one that eases off at the end.

true: True
consequence: The ending carries heavy weight in memory. A shorter total length carries almost none.

false: False
consequence: Total time in pain barely shows up in memory. The ending and the peak do most of the work.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: A sharp ending colours a whole memory. A long, gently fading ending can leave a gentler memory, even with more total pain.
hint: Think about which of the two patients walks out with a kinder memory of it.

@text
Every package has turned on the same quiet idea.
The fast mind keeps running the day from a crowd of shortcuts, and the slow mind only sometimes walks in.
The open question is which of those shortcuts is quietly picking the next decision already forming, and whether anyone would notice if one of them stopped.
